# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carabine-à-tige
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The **8×50mmR Lebel** (8mm Lebel) (designated as the **8 × 51 R Lebel** by the C.I.P.) rifle cartridge was the first smokeless powder cartridge to be made and adopted by any country.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11×59mmR Gras black powder cartridge, the smokeless 8mm Lebel cartridge started a revolution in military rifle ammunition.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Standard 8mm Lebel military ammunition was also the first rifle ammunition to feature a spitzer boat tail bullet (*balle* D), which was adopted in 1898.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The long-range ballistic performance of the 8mm Lebel bullet itself was exceptional for its time.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] For use in the magazine tube-fed early Lebel rifle, the 8 mm case was designed to protect against accidental percussion inside the tube magazine by a circular groove around the primer cup which caught the tip of the following pointed bullet.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] However, the shape of its rimmed bottle-necked case, having been designed for the Lebel rifle's tube magazine, also precluded truly efficient vertical stacking inside a vertical magazine.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The bolt thrust of the 8mm Lebel is relatively high compared to many other service rounds used in the early 20th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Although it was once revolutionary, the 8mm Lebel was declared obsolete after World War I and was soon after replaced with the 7.5×54mm French round.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] There were two historical commercially available 8mm Lebel cartridges: one for the Lebel Model 1886 rifle, and one for the Modèle 1892 revolver.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] They are two entirely different cartridges and are not interchangeable.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The term "8mm Lebel" for the French Mle 1892 revolver ammunition, is only applied outside France for commercial reasons and has nothing to do with the Lebel rifle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] However, the term "8mm Lebel", used to identify a rifle cartridge, is widely recognized to distinguish the French rifle cartridge from other 8 mm rifle cartridges, such as the 8×50mmR Mannlicher cartridge used by Austria-Hungary and its successor states.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The cartridge for the tube-fed long arm was originally loaded with a 15.0 g (232 grains) cupro-nickel-jacketed, lead-cored, flat-nosed, wadcutter-style bullet, called "*balle M*", which had been designed by Lieutenant Colonel Nicolas Lebel.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The flat point (flat nose or tip) of this bullet had been designed to be safe inside the newly commissioned rifle's tube magazine.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] It was propelled by the first practical smokeless, nitrocellulose-based powder (*Poudre B*), as developed by Paul Vieille in 1884.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The ballistic performance and range of *balle M* with the new propellant eclipsed all the previous military ammunitions in existence at the time (1886).
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] This *balle M* was replaced in 1898 by a new design, a 12.8 g (198 grains) 90/10 bronze mono-metal, pointed (spitzer) boat-tail bullet called "*balle D*", which provided a flatter trajectory and improved long-range performance.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Designed at the Atelier de Puteaux (APX) by Captain Georges Desaleux, the *balle D* was the first pointed *and* boat-tailed bullet to be placed into service by any military.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Later on in 1912, the round was improved into the *balle D am* ("am" stands for "*amorçage modifié*" or "modified primer"), done by crimping the primer in more deeply to prevent primer expulsions when fired in machine guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] This ammunition was in near-universal service during World War I (1914–1918) in all Lebel-caliber weapons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The *balle D am* ammunition was followed in 1932 by *balle N* ammunition, which featured a lead-cored, cupro-nickel-over-steel-jacketed, pointed boat-tail bullet weighing 15.0 g (232 grains).
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] It was thicker (8.3 mm instead of 8.17) and was held into a case that had a slightly larger neck diameter than that for the older *balle D am* ammunition.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The new *balle N* was again heavier than the *balle D am*, and had been designed to improve the long-range performance of the issued Hotchkiss machine guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Rechambering practically all French Lebel-caliber rifles and carbines to use the "N"-type ammunition was carried out during the 1930s.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] A *balle T* (tracer ammunition) and *balle P* armor-piercing rounds were also produced, along with blank and reduced charge cartridges.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] In order to safely accommodate pointed (spitzer) bullets inside the Lebel rifle magazine, a circular groove was machined around each primer cup at the case base on both *balle D am* and *balle N* ammunitions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The role of that circular groove is to receive the pointed bullet tip of the following round loaded inside the tube magazine, and keep it *at the side* of the case base of the previous cartridge, so the tip does not easily slide to the base center where the primer is located.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The tapered form of the case itself did help too to keep pointed tips away from the primer cup of a round in front of another in the tube.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Furthermore, all *balle D* and *balle M* French military ammunitions featured *convex primer covers* which are crimped in over the primer itself.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Those small covers are not noticeable, but do provide a second effective protection against accidental primer percussion inside the Lebel's tube magazine.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Wartime experiences (1914–1918) involving hundreds of millions of Lebel rounds fired in combat have entirely confirmed the effectiveness of these protections.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] While revolutionary for its time in terms of ballistic performance, the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge had its drawbacks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11mm Gras rifle cartridge case, it was an odd design, with a thick rim and a rapid double taper.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] This made it more difficult to feed from standard magazine firearms such as the Berthier rifles and the Chauchat machine guns, and is the reason for the distinct curvature in the magazines of those firearms.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The Lebel rifle from which it was fired was also rather outdated by the time *balle D*, let alone the *balle N*, came along.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] A *balle N* round can only be fired from Lebel or Berthier rifles, if the chamber has been reamed to accept the larger neck of the N-type cartridge.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Such weapons are stamped *N* on top of the barrel, just in front of the receiver and behind the rear sight.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The *balle N* ammunition is identifiable by the fact that the bullet, while pointed like the solid-brass *balle D*, is lead-cored and jacketed with soft steel.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] While newly manufactured 8×50mmR Lebel ammunition has become available in the U.S., reloadable cartridge cases can also be produced by reforming .348 Winchester brass.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The 8mm Lebel round produced by Prvi Partizan is of excellent quality and replicates the performance of the original round.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] However, Privi Partizan's *older style* brass cases lack the circular groove around the primer cup, so reloaders use round-nosed or flat-nosed bullets when producing handloads for the tube-magazine Lebel rifles with these cases.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] The older Privi Partizan cases loaded with spire point bullets should only be fired single shot.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] More recently, Privi Partizan manufactured Lebel ammunition with spitzer bullets do incorporate the circular groove at the base, and are safe when stacked in the box-magazine of Berthier rifles and the tubular magazine of Lebel rifles.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] Newer cases with circular groove follow the *balle D* specifications, and shooters may use the magazine for loading.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] 1929 (7.5 French) cartridge was introduced.
[src:carabine-à-tige/8mm-lebel] This made the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge obsolete, but due to post-World War I financial constraints and political neglect, it was not introduced as a rifle cartridge until the adoption, just before World War II, of the MAS-36 rifle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The purpose of ammunition is to project a force against a selected target to have an effect (usually, but not always, lethal).
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] An example of ammunition is the firearm cartridge, which includes all components required to deliver the weapon's effect in a single package.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Until the 20th century, black powder was the most common propellant used, but it has now been replaced in nearly all cases by modern compounds.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Ammunition comes in a wide range of sizes and types and is often designed to work only with specific weapon systems.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] However, there are internationally recognized standards for certain ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) that enable their use across different weapons and by different users.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] There are also specific types of ammunition that are designed to have a specialized effect on a target, such as armor-piercing shells and tracer ammunition, used only in certain circumstances.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Ammunition is commonly labeled or colored in a specific manner to assist in its identification and to prevent the wrong ammunition types from being used accidentally or inappropriately.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The term *ammunition* dates back to the mid-17th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The word comes from the French *la munition*, for the material used for war.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] *Ammunition* and *munition* are often used interchangeably, although *munition* now usually refers to the actual weapons system with the ammunition required to operate it.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] In some languages other than English ammunition is still referred to as munition, such as: Dutch ("*munitie*"), French ("*munitions*"), German ("*Munition*"), Italian ("*munizione*") and Portuguese ("*munição*").
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Ammunition design has evolved throughout history as different weapons have been developed and different effects required.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Historically, ammunition was of relatively simple design and build (e.g., sling-shot, stones hurled by catapults), but as weapon designs developed (e.g., rifling) and became more refined, the need for more specialized ammunition increased.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Modern ammunition can vary significantly in quality but is usually manufactured to very high standards.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] For example, ammunition for hunting can be designed to expand inside a target, maximizing the damage inflicted by one round.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Anti-personnel shells are designed to fragment into many pieces and can affect a large area.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Armor-piercing rounds are specially hardened to penetrate armor, while smoke ammunition creates a fog that screens people from view.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] More generic ammunition (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) can often be modified slightly to achieve a more specific effect (e.g., tracer, incendiary), whilst larger explosive rounds can be altered by using different fuzes.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The term *fuze* refers to the detonator of an explosive round or shell.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The spelling is different in British English and American English (fuse/fuze respectively), and they are unrelated to a fuse (electrical).
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] A fuse was earlier used to ignite the propellant (e.g., such as on a firework) until the advent of more reliable systems, such as the primer or igniter that is used in most modern ammunition.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The fuze of a weapon can be used to alter how the ammunition works.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] These allow a single ammunition type to be altered to suit the situation it is required for.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] There are many fuze designs, ranging from simple mechanical to complex radar- and barometric-based systems.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Fuzes are typically armed by the acceleration force of firing the projectile and are armed several meters after clearing the weapon's bore.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] This helps to ensure the ammunition is safer to handle when loading into the weapon and reduces the chance of the detonator firing before the ammunition has cleared the weapon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The propellant is the component of ammunition that is activated inside the weapon and provides the kinetic energy required to move the projectile from the weapon to the target.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] In recent years, compressed gas, magnetic energy, and electrical energy have been used as propellants.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Until the 20th century, gunpowder was the most common propellant in ammunition.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] However, it has since been replaced by a wide range of fast-burning compounds that are more reliable and efficient.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The propellant charge is distinct from the projectile charge, which is activated by the fuze, which causes the ammunition effect (e.g., the exploding of an artillery round).
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The cartridge is the container that holds the projectile and propellant.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Not all ammunition types have a cartridge case.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] In its place, a wide range of materials can be used to contain the explosives and parts.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] With some large weapons, the ammunition components are stored separately until loaded into the weapon system for firing.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] With small arms, caseless ammunition can reduce the weight and cost of ammunition and simplify the firing process, increasing the firing rate, but the technology is still maturing and has functional issues.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The projectile is the part of the ammunition that leaves the weapon and affects the target.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] This effect is usually either kinetic (e.g., as with a standard bullet) or explosive.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] An ammunition dump is a military facility for storing live ammunition and explosives to be distributed and used at a later date.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Such a storage facility is extremely hazardous, with a high risk of accidents during unloading, packing, and transferring the ammunition.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] In the event of a fire or explosion, the site and its surrounding area are immediately evacuated, and the stored ammunition is left to detonate completely, with limited firefighting attempts from a safe distance.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] In large facilities, there may be a flooding system to extinguish a fire or prevent an explosion automatically.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Typically, an ammunition dump will have a large buffer zone surrounding it to avoid casualties in the event of an accident.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] There will also be perimeter security measures in place to prevent unauthorized personnel from accessing the area and to guard against potential threats from enemy forces.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] A magazine is a place where a quantity of ammunition or other explosive material is stored temporarily before being used.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The term may be used for a facility that stores large quantities of ammunition, although this is normally referred to as an ammunition dump.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Magazines are typically located in the field for quick access when engaging the enemy.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The ammunition storage area on a warship is referred to as the "ship's magazine".
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] On a smaller scale, magazine is also the name given to the ammunition storage and feeding device of a repeating firearm.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Gunpowder must be stored in a dry place (stable room temperature) to keep it usable for at least 10 years.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] It is also recommended to avoid hot places, because friction or heat might ignite a spark and cause an explosion.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The standard weapon of a modern soldier is an assault rifle, which, like other small arms, uses cartridge ammunition sized for the weapon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Ammunition is carried on the person in box magazines specific to the weapon, ammunition boxes, pouches, or bandoliers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The amount of ammunition carried depends on the soldier's strength, the expected action required, and the ammunition's ability to move through the logistical chain to replenish the supply.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] A soldier may also carry a smaller amount of specialized ammunition for heavier weapons, such as machine guns and mortars, thereby spreading the burden of squad weapons among many people.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Too little ammunition threatens the mission, while too much limits the soldier's mobility and also threatens the mission.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] A shell is a payload-carrying projectile which, as opposed to a shot, contains explosives or other fillings, in use since the 19th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Artillery shells are ammunition that is designed to be fired from artillery, which has an effect over long distances, usually indirectly (i.e., out of sight of the target).
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] There are many different types of artillery ammunition, but they are usually high-explosive and designed to shatter into fragments on impact to maximize damage.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The fuze on an artillery shell can alter how it explodes or behaves, giving it a more specialized effect.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Common types of artillery ammunition include high explosive, smoke, illumination, and practice rounds.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Some artillery rounds are designed as cluster munitions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Artillery ammunition will almost always include a projectile (the only exception being demonstration or blank rounds), fuze, and propellant of some form.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] When a cartridge case is not used, another method of containing the propellant bags is used, usually in a breech-loading weapon; see Breechloader.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Tank ammunition was developed in World War I as tanks first appeared on the battlefield.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The development of shaped charges has had a significant impact on anti-tank ammunition design, now common in both tank-fired ammunition and in anti-tank missiles, including anti-tank guided missiles.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Naval weapons were originally the same as many land-based weapons, but the ammunition was designed for specific use, such as a solid shot designed to hole an enemy ship and chain-shot to cut rigging and sails.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Modern naval engagements have occurred over far longer distances than historic battles, so as ship armor has increased in strength and thickness, the ammunition to defeat it has also changed.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Naval ammunition is now designed to reach very high velocities (to improve its armor-piercing abilities) and may have specialized fuzes to defeat specific types of vessels.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] However, due to the extended ranges at which modern naval combat may occur, guided missiles have largely supplanted guns and shells.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] With every successive improvement in military arms, a corresponding change has occurred in the method of supplying ammunition in the required quantities.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] As soon as projectiles were required (such as javelins and arrows), there needed to be a method of replenishment.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] When non-specialized, interchangeable, or recoverable ammunition was used (e.g., arrows), it was possible to pick up spent arrows (both friendly and enemy) and reuse them.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] However, with the advent of explosive or non-recoverable ammunition, this was no longer possible, and new ammunition supplies would be needed.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The weight of ammunition required, particularly for artillery shells, can be considerable, necessitating extra time to replenish supplies.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] In modern times, there has been an increase in the standardization of many ammunition types among allies (e.g., the NATO Standardization Agreement) that has enabled the sharing of ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO).
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] As of 2013, lead-based ammunition production is the second-largest annual use of lead in the US, accounting for over 60,000 metric tons consumed in 2012.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Lead bullets that miss their target or remain in a carcass or body that was never retrieved can enter environmental systems and become toxic to wildlife.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] The US military has experimented with replacing lead with copper as a slug in their green bullets which reduces the dangers posed by lead in the environment as a result of artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Since 2010, this has eliminated over 2000 tons of lead in waste streams.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Hunters are also encouraged to use monolithic bullets, which exclude any lead content.
[src:carabine-à-tige/ammunition] Unexploded ammunition can remain active for a very long time and poses a significant threat to both humans and the environment.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] Collaborating with Charles Renard, Krebs piloted the first fully controlled free-flight made in the French Army airship *La France*, which was designed in 1884.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight covered 8 km (5.0 mi) in 23 minutes.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight landed back at its starting point.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] On its seven flights the *La France* dirigible returned five times to its starting point.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs and Renard shared the 1886 Ponti prize of the French *Académie des sciences* for their contribution to aerostation.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In Verne's 1886 novel *Robur The Conqueror*, he writes of "the striking experiments of Captain Krebs and Captain Renard".
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1888 Krebs and Gustave Zédé designed the first modern French submarine, the *Gymnote*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] The submarine was fitted with the first naval periscope and the first naval electric gyrocompass.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] The latter allowed the *Gymnote* to force a naval block in 1890.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] From 1884 to 1897 Arthur Krebs modernized the *Ville de Paris* fire department; not only its equipment but its organisation as well.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] His work left a lasting impression in this elite corps.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In May 1896 Arthur Krebs patented a new automobile, fitted with an electromagnetic gearbox and a layout of the front wheels which re-centred them when the steering wheel was left alone.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] Today this is known as the Castor angle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] The Panhard et Levassor company acquired a license to build 500 cars under the name of Clement-Panhard between 1898 and 1902 featuring this innovation.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs succeeded Levassor as Panhard et Levassor's general manager from 1897 to 1916.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] He transformed the Panhard et Levassor Company into one of the largest and most profitable automobile manufacturers before World War I.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1898 Krebs replaced the tiller with an inclined steering wheel for the Panhard et Levassor car he designed for the Paris-Amsterdam race which ran from 7 to 13 July 1898.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] Fernand Charron won that race on a four-cylinder Panhard et Levassor.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] At the end of 1898, C S Rolls introduced the first car in Britain fitted with wheel steering when he imported a 6 hp Panhard et Levassor from France.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1902 Krebs invented the automatic diaphragm carburettor which gave cars continuous power during acceleration by providing a constant air-fuel ratio at all times; this also led to dramatic improvement in fuel economy.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1906 Krebs traveled to the United States to plead in the Selden Case, associated with Henry Ford.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] Also, Krebs contributed significantly to improve the Systeme Panhard (engine in front, rear wheel drive) which became universally adopted before World War II.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1909 Krebs became interested in the Knight patent (sleeve valve engine).
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] He was also the first person in France to build that type of engine which Panhard et Levassor would produce during the thirty years leading up to World War II.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] He made contributions to automotive racing with his powerful cars and motorboats.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911 Krebs invented the first elastomeric flexible coupling (cf.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] It is known in French as the *Flector* joint.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] This device is still widely used today in industry for power transmission as a *tyre coupling*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck was meant for military and civil purposes.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911, jointly with the Chatillon Co, Krebs designed the *Tracteur Chatillon-Panhard* all-terrain truck.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck had four wheel drive and four wheel steering and many were used during World War I as artillery tractors.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs also utilized his former military membership to supply the French Army with engines and vehicles including the 1904 Genty Armored car, the 1916 St Chamond tank, the Chatillon-Panhard 4x4 truck, and others.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1960, the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) named Krebs Glacier, a glacier flowing west into the head of Charlotte Bay on the west coast of Graham Land in the Antarctic continent, after Krebs.
[src:carabine-à-tige/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1934, several months before Arthur Krebs's death, he was made a Commandeur of the Legion of Honour for his work in Aeronautics and for his contributions to the automotive industry.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] The **Canet guns** were a series of weapon systems developed by Gustave Canet, who worked as an engineer from 1872 to 1881 for the London Ordnance Works, then for Forges et Chantiers de la Méditerranée, and from 1897 to 1907 for Schneider et Cie of Le Creusot.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] Canet developed a 12.6 in (32 cm) 38 cal naval gun, an extremely powerful weapon for its time, specifically for the export market.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] The gun was first selected by the Spanish Navy in 1884 as part of a large naval expansion program which called for six new battleships.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] The Spanish armaments firm Hontoria obtained a manufacturing license to produce the weapon, but due to budgetary reasons, only one vessel, the *Pelayo*, was completed.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] Canet was more successful in sales to the Empire of Japan, when the gun was selected by the French military advisor and naval architect Louis-Émile Bertin as the main battery of the *Matsushima*-class cruiser, new type of cruiser he had designed in 1887.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] The usage was consistent with the Jeune École philosophy, which advocated placing overwhelming firepower (strong guns, torpedoes) on relatively small ships.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] This philosophy was of great interest to the Imperial Japanese Navy, which lacked the resources at the time to purchase modern pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] The guns supplied to Japan equipped the cruisers *Matsushima*, *Itsukushima*, and *Hashidate*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] Each gun weighed 67 tons, and had a barrel 12 metres (39 ft) long, firing a 112 cm (44 in) long projectile with weight of 350 kg (770 lb) (or 449 kg (990 lb) high explosive) for an effective range of 8,000 metres (26,000 ft).
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] The guns proved only marginally successful during the First Sino-Japanese War, due to a slow rate of fire, and numerous mechanical problems.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] The guns could not be aimed abeam, as their weight would cause the ship to roll over when fired.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] In combat, gunners were able to fire only around one shot per hour due to the time it took to reload.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canet-guns] Canet is also known for developing the Schneider-Canet gun system for 75 mm iron BL mountain guns, and rapid-fire 120 mm and 152 mm guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] A **cannon** (plural either *cannons* or *cannon*) is a large-caliber gun classified as a type of artillery, which usually launches a projectile using explosive chemical propellant.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Gunpowder ("black powder") was the primary propellant before the invention of smokeless powder during the late 19th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons vary in gauge, effective range, mobility, rate of fire, angle of fire and firepower; different forms of cannon combine and balance these attributes in varying degrees, depending on their intended use on the battlefield.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] A cannon is a type of heavy artillery weapon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from several languages, in which the original definition can usually be translated as *tube*, *cane*, or *reed*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of cannons may have appeared in Song dynasty China as early as the 12th century; however, solid archaeological and documentary evidence of cannons do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In 1288, Yuan dynasty troops are recorded to have used hand cannons in combat, and the earliest extant cannon bearing a date of production comes from the same period.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century, cannons were widespread throughout Eurasia.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons were used primarily as anti-infantry weapons until around 1374, when large cannons were recorded to have breached walls for the first time in Europe.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons featured prominently as siege weapons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In 1464 a 16,000 kg (35,000 lb) cannon known as the Great Turkish Bombard was created in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons as field artillery became more important after 1453 when cannons broke down the walls of the Roman Empire's capital, with the introduction of limber, which greatly improved cannon maneuverability and mobility.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] European cannons reached their longer, lighter, more accurate, and more efficient "classic form" around 1480.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] This classic European cannon design stayed relatively consistent in form with minor changes until the 1750s.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In the modern era, the term *cannon* has fallen into disuse, replaced by *guns* or *artillery*, if not a more specific term such as howitzer or mortar, except for automatic weapons called autocannons, usually firing explosive shells of larger caliber than machine-gun bullets.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from the Old Italian word *cannone*, meaning "large tube", which came from the Latin *canna*, in turn originating from the Greek κάννα (*kanna*), "reed", and then generalised to mean any hollow tube-like object.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The word has been used to refer to a gun since 1326 in Italy and 1418 in England.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The plural forms *cannons* and *cannon* are both correct.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The cannon may have appeared as early as the 12th century in China, and was probably a parallel development or evolution of the fire-lance, a short ranged anti-personnel weapon combining a gunpowder-filled tube and a polearm.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Projectiles such as iron scraps or porcelain shards, mixed together with the gunpowder ("co-viative"), were placed in fire lance barrels at some point, and eventually, the paper and bamboo materials of fire lance barrels were replaced by metal.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of a cannon is a sculpture from the Dazu Rock Carvings in Sichuan dated to 1128, however, the earliest archaeological samples and textual accounts do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The primary extant specimens of cannon from the 13th century are the Wuwei Bronze Cannon dated to 1227, the Heilongjiang hand cannon dated to 1288, and the Xanadu Gun dated to 1298.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] However, only the Xanadu gun contains an inscription bearing a date of production, so it is considered the earliest confirmed extant cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Xanadu Gun is 34.7 cm (13.7 in) in length and weighs 6.2 kg (14 lb).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The other cannons are dated using contextual evidence.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Heilongjiang hand cannon is also often considered by some to be the oldest firearm since it was unearthed near the area where the *History of Yuan* reports a battle took place involving hand cannons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] According to the *History of Yuan*, in 1288, a Jurchen commander by the name of Li Ting led troops armed with hand cannons into battle against the rebel prince Nayan.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Chen Bingying argues there were no guns before 1259, while Dang Shoushan believes the Wuwei gun and other Western Xia era samples point to the appearance of guns by 1220, and Stephen Haw goes even further by stating that guns were developed as early as 1200.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Sinologist Joseph Needham and renaissance siege expert Thomas Arnold provide a more conservative estimate of around 1280 for the appearance of the "true" cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Whether or not any of these are correct, it seems likely that the gun was born sometime during the 13th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] References to cannons proliferated throughout China in the following centuries.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In 1341 Xian Zhang wrote a poem called *The Iron Cannon Affair* describing a cannonball fired from an eruptor which could "pierce the heart or belly when striking a man or horse, and even transfix several persons at once." By the 1350s the cannon was used extensively in Chinese warfare.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In 1358 the Ming army failed to take a city due to its garrisons' usage of cannon, however, they themselves would use cannon, in the thousands, later on during the siege of Suzhou in 1366.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Mongol invasion of Java in 1293 brought gunpowder technology to the Nusantara archipelago in the form of cannon (Chinese: *Pao*).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] During the Ming dynasty cannons were used in riverine warfare at the Battle of Lake Poyang.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] One shipwreck in Shandong had a cannon dated to 1377 and an anchor dated to 1372.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] From the 13th to 15th centuries cannon-armed Chinese ships also travelled throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannon appeared in Đại Việt by 1390 at the latest.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The first of the western cannon to be introduced were breech-loaders in the early 16th century, which the Chinese began producing themselves by 1523 and improved on by including composite metal construction in their making.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Japan did not acquire cannon until 1510 when a monk brought one back from China, and did not produce any in appreciable numbers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] During the 1593 siege of Pyongyang, 40,000 Ming troops deployed a variety of cannons against Japanese troops.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Despite their defensive advantage and the use of arquebus by Japanese soldiers, the Japanese were at a severe disadvantage due to their lack of cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Throughout the Japanese invasions of Korea (1592–1598), the Ming–Joseon coalition used artillery widely in land and naval battles, including on the turtle ships of Yi Sun-sin.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] According to Ivan Petlin, the first Russian envoy to Beijing, in September 1619, the city was armed with large cannon with cannonballs weighing more than 30 kg (66 lb).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Outside of China, the earliest texts to mention gunpowder are Roger Bacon's *Opus Majus* (1267) and *Opus Tertium* in what has been interpreted as references to firecrackers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In the early 20th century, a British artillery officer proposed that another work tentatively attributed to Bacon, *Epistola de Secretis Operibus Artis et Naturae, et de Nullitate Magiae*, dated to 1247, contained an encrypted formula for gunpowder hidden in the text.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] These claims have been disputed by science historians.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In any case, the formula itself is not useful for firearms or even firecrackers, burning slowly and producing mostly smoke.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] There is a record of a gun in Europe dating to 1322 that was discovered in the nineteenth century, but the artifact has since been lost.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In the same year, another similar illustration showed a darker gun being set off by a group of knights, in another work of de Milemete's, *De secretis secretorum Aristotelis*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] On 11 February of that same year, the Signoria of Florence appointed two officers to obtain *canones de mettallo* and ammunition for the town's defence.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In the following year a document from the Turin area recorded a certain amount was paid "for the making of a certain instrument or device made by Friar Marcello for the projection of pellets of lead".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] A reference from 1331 describes an attack mounted by two Germanic knights on Cividale del Friuli, using man-portable gunpowder weapons of some sort.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The 1320s seem to have been the takeoff point for guns in Europe according to most modern military historians.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Scholars suggest that the lack of gunpowder weapons in a well-travelled Venetian's catalogue for a new crusade in 1321 implies that guns were unknown in Europe up until this point, further solidifying the 1320 mark, however more evidence in this area may be forthcoming in the future.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The oldest extant cannon in Europe is a small bronze example unearthed in Loshult, Scania in southern Sweden.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] It dates from the early-mid 14th century, and is currently in the Swedish History Museum in Stockholm.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Early cannons in Europe often shot arrows and were known by an assortment of names such as *pot-de-fer*, *tonnoire*, *ribaldis*, and *büszenpyle*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The *ribaldis*, which shot large arrows and simplistic grapeshot, were first mentioned in the English Privy Wardrobe accounts during preparations for the Battle of Crécy, between 1345 and 1346.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Florentine Giovanni Villani recounts their destructiveness, indicating that by the end of the battle, "the whole plain was covered by men struck down by arrows and cannon balls".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Similar cannon were also used at the siege of Calais (1346–47), although it was not until the 1380s that the *ribaudekin* clearly became mounted on wheels.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Battle of Crécy which pitted the English against the French in 1346 featured the early use of cannon which helped the longbowmen repulse a large force of Genoese crossbowmen deployed by the French.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The English originally intended to use the cannon against cavalry sent to attack their archers, thinking that the loud noises produced by their cannon would panic the advancing horses along with killing the knights atop them.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Early cannons could also be used for more than simply killing men and scaring horses.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] English cannon were used defensively in 1346 during the siege of Breteuil to launch fire onto an advancing siege tower.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In this way, cannons could be used to burn down siege equipment before it reached the fortifications.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The use of cannons to shoot fire could also be used offensively as another battle involved the setting of a castle ablaze with similar methods.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The particular incendiary used in these projectiles was most likely a gunpowder mixture.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] This is one area where early Chinese and European cannons share a similarity as both were possibly used to shoot fire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Early European cannons were rather small, dwarfed by the bombards, which would come later.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In fact, it is possible that the cannons used at Crécy were capable of being moved rather quickly as there is an anonymous chronicle that notes the guns being used to attack the French camp, indicating that they would have been mobile enough to press the attack.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] These smaller cannons would eventually give way to larger, wall-breaching guns by the end of the 1300s.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] There is no clear consensus on when the cannon first appeared in the Islamic world, with dates ranging from 1260 to the mid-14th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] However, some scholars do not accept these early dates.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] While the date of its first appearance is not entirely clear, the general consensus among most historians is that there is no doubt the Mamluk forces were using cannon by 1342.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Other accounts may have also mentioned the use of cannon in the early 14th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] An Arabic text dating to 1320–1350 describes a type of gunpowder weapon called a *midfa* which uses gunpowder to shoot projectiles out of a tube at the end of a stock.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Some scholars consider this a hand cannon while others dispute this claim.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Nasrid army besieging Elche in 1331 made use of "iron pellets shot with fire".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] According to historian Ahmad Y. al-Hassan, during the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, the Mamluks used cannon against the Mongols.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] He claims that this was "the first cannon in history" and used a gunpowder formula almost identical to the ideal composition for explosive gunpowder.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] He also argues that this was not known in China or Europe until much later.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Al-Hassan further claims that the earliest textual evidence of cannon is from the Middle East, based on earlier originals which report hand-held cannons being used by the Mamluks at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Such an early date is not accepted by some historians, including David Ayalon, Iqtidar Alam Khan, Joseph Needham and Tonio Andrade.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Khan argues that it was the Mongols who introduced gunpowder to the Islamic world, and believes cannon only reached Mamluk Egypt in the 1370s.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Needham argued that the term *midfa*, dated to textual sources from 1342 to 1352, did not refer to true hand-guns or bombards, and that contemporary accounts of a metal-barrel cannon in the Islamic world did not occur until 1365.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Similarly, Andrade dates the textual appearance of cannons in middle eastern sources to the 1360s.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Gabor Ágoston and David Ayalon note that the Mamluks had certainly used siege cannons by 1342 or the 1360s, respectively, but earlier uses of cannons in the Islamic World are vague with a possible appearance in the Emirate of Granada by the 1320s and 1330s, though evidence is inconclusive.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Ibn Khaldun reported the use of cannon as siege machines by the Marinid sultan Abu Yaqub Yusuf at the siege of Sijilmasa in 1274.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The passage by Ibn Khaldun on the Marinid siege of Sijilmassa in 1274 occurs as follows: "[The Sultan] installed siege engines ... and gunpowder engines ..., which project small balls of iron.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] These balls are ejected from a chamber ... placed in front of a kindling fire of gunpowder; this happens by a strange property which attributes all actions to the power of the Creator." The source is not contemporary and was written a century later, around 1382.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Needham believes Ibn Khaldun was speaking of fire lances rather than hand cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Ottoman Empire made good use of cannon as siege artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Sixty-eight super-sized bombards were used by Mehmed the Conqueror to capture Constantinople in 1453.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Jim Bradbury argues that Urban, a Hungarian cannon engineer, introduced this cannon from Central Europe to the Ottoman realm; according to Paul Hammer, however, it could have been introduced from other Islamic countries which had earlier used cannons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] These cannons could fire heavy stone balls a mile, and the sound of their blast could reportedly be heard from a distance of 10 miles (16 km).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Shkodëran historian Marin Barleti discusses Turkish bombards at length in his book *De obsidione Scodrensi* (1504), describing the 1478–79 siege of Shkodra in which eleven bombards and two mortars were employed.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Ottomans also used cannon to control passage of ships through the Bosphorus strait.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Ottoman cannons also proved effective at stopping crusaders at Varna in 1444 and Kosovo in 1448 despite the presence of European cannon in the former case.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The similar Dardanelles Guns (for the location) were created by Munir Ali in 1464 and were still in use during the Anglo-Turkish War (1807–1809).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] These were cast in bronze into two parts: the chase (the barrel) and the breech, which combined weighed 18.4 tonnes.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The two parts were screwed together using levers to facilitate moving it.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Fathullah Shirazi, a Persian inhabitant of India who worked for Akbar in the Mughal Empire, developed a volley gun in the 16th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] While there is evidence of cannons in Iran as early as 1405 they were not widespread.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] This changed following the increased use of firearms by Shah Ismail I, and the Iranian army used 500 cannons by the 1620s, probably captured from the Ottomans or acquired by allies in Europe.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] By 1443, Iranians were also making some of their own cannon, as Mir Khawand wrote of a 1200 kg metal piece being made by an Iranian *rikhtegar* which was most likely a cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Due to the difficulties of transporting cannon in mountainous terrain, their use was less common compared to their use in Europe.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Documentary evidence of cannons in Russia does not appear until 1382 and they were used only in sieges, often by the defenders.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] It was not until 1475 when Ivan III established the first Russian cannon foundry in Moscow that they began to produce cannons natively.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The earliest surviving cannon from Russia dates to 1485.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Later on, large cannons were known as bombards, ranging from three to five feet in length and were used by Dubrovnik and Kotor in defence during the later 14th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The first bombards were made of iron, but bronze became more prevalent as it was recognized as more stable and capable of propelling stones weighing as much as 45 kilograms (99 lb).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Around the same period, the Byzantine Empire began to accumulate its own cannon to face the Ottoman Empire, starting with medium-sized cannon 3 feet (0.91 m) long and of 10 in calibre.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The earliest reliable recorded use of artillery in the region was against the Ottoman siege of Constantinople in 1396, forcing the Ottomans to withdraw.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Ottomans acquired their own cannon and laid siege to the Byzantine capital again in 1422.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] By 1453, the Ottomans used 68 Hungarian-made cannon for the 55-day bombardment of the walls of Constantinople, "hurling the pieces everywhere and killing those who happened to be nearby".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The largest of their cannons was the Great Turkish Bombard, which required an operating crew of 200 men and 70 oxen, and 10,000 men to transport it.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Gunpowder made the formerly devastating Greek fire obsolete, and with the final fall of Constantinople—which was protected by what were once the strongest walls in Europe—on 29 May 1453, "it was the end of an era in more ways than one".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons were introduced to the Javanese Majapahit Empire when Kublai Khan's Mongol-Chinese army under the leadership of Ike Mese sought to invade Java in 1293.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] *History of Yuan* mentioned that the Mongol used a weapon called *p'ao* against Daha forces.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] This weapon is interpreted differently by researchers, it may be a trebuchet that throws thunderclap bombs, firearms, cannons, or rockets.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] It is possible that the gunpowder weapons carried by the Mongol–Chinese troops amounted to more than one type.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Thomas Stamford Raffles wrote in *The History of Java* that in 1247 saka (1325 AD), cannons were widely used in Java especially by the Majapahit.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] It is recorded that the small kingdoms in Java that sought the protection of Majapahit had to hand over their cannons to the Majapahit.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Majapahit under *Mahapatih* (prime minister) Gajah Mada (in office 1331–1364) utilized gunpowder technology obtained from Yuan dynasty for use in naval fleet.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Mongol-Chinese gunpowder technology of Yuan dynasty resulted in eastern-style cetbang which is similar to Chinese cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Swivel guns however, only developed in the archipelago because of the close maritime relations of the Nusantara archipelago with the territory of West India after 1460 AD, which brought new types of gunpowder weapons to the archipelago, likely through Arab intermediaries.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] This weapon seems to be cannon and gun of Ottoman tradition, for example the prangi, which is a breech-loading swivel gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] A new type of cetbang, called the western-style cetbang, was derived from the Turkish prangi.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Just like prangi, this cetbang is a breech-loading swivel gun made of bronze or iron, firing single rounds or scattershots (a large number of small bullets).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons derived from western-style cetbang can be found in Nusantara, among others were lantaka and lela.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Most lantakas were made of bronze and the earliest ones were breech-loaded.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] There is a trend toward muzzle-loading weapons during colonial times.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] When the Portuguese came to the archipelago, they referred to the breech-loading swivel gun as *berço*, while the Spaniards call it *verso*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] A pole gun (*bedil tombak*) was recorded as being used by Java in 1413.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] 1514 said that the inhabitants of Java were great masters in casting artillery and very good artillerymen.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] They made many one-pounder cannon (*cetbang* or *rentaka*), long muskets, *spingarde* (arquebus), *schioppi* (hand cannon), Greek fire, guns (cannon), and other fireworks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Every place was considered excellent in casting artillery, and in the knowledge of using it.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In 1513, the Javanese fleet led by Pati Unus sailed to attack Portuguese Malacca "with much artillery made in Java, for the Javanese are skilled in founding and casting, and in all works in iron, over and above what they have in India".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] By early 16th century, the Javanese already locally-producing large guns, some of them still survived until the present day and dubbed as "sacred cannon" or "holy cannon".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] These cannons varied between 180- and 260-pounders, weighing anywhere between 3 and 8 tons, length of them between 3 and 6 m (9.8 and 19.7 ft).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons were used by the Ayutthaya Kingdom in 1352 during its invasion of the Khmer Empire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Within a decade large quantities of gunpowder could be found in the Khmer Empire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century firearms were also used by the Trần dynasty.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Saltpeter harvesting was recorded by Dutch and German travellers as being common in even the smallest villages and was collected from the decomposition process of large dung hills specifically piled for the purpose.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The Dutch punishment for possession of non-permitted gunpowder appears to have been amputation.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Ownership and manufacture of gunpowder was later prohibited by the colonial Dutch occupiers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] According to colonel McKenzie quoted in Sir Thomas Stamford Raffles' *The History of Java* (1817), the purest sulfur was supplied from a crater from a mountain near the straits of Bali.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In Africa, the Adal Sultanate and the Abyssinian Empire both deployed cannons during the Adal-Abyssinian War.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Imported from Arabia, and the wider Islamic world, the Adalites led by Ahmed ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi were the first African power to introduce cannon warfare to the African continent.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Later on as the Portuguese Empire entered the war it would supply and train the Abyssinians with cannons, while the Ottoman Empire sent soldiers and cannon to back Adal.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] The conflict proved, through their use on both sides, the value of firearms such as the matchlock musket, cannon, and the arquebus over traditional weapons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] While previous smaller guns could burn down structures with fire, larger and more powerful cannons forced engineers to develop stronger castle walls from enemy attacks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons were used for other purposes, as fortifications began using cannons as defensive instruments.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In India, the fort of Raicher had gun ports built into its walls to accommodate the use of defensive cannons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In *The Art of War*, Niccolò Machiavelli opined that field artillery forced an army to take up a defensive posture and opposed a more ideal offensive stance.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Machiavelli's concerns can be seen in the criticisms of Portuguese mortars being used in India during the sixteenth century as lack of mobility was one of the key problems with the design.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] In Russia the early cannons were again placed in forts as a defensive tool.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p01] Cannons were also difficult to move around in mountainous regions; offensives conducted with such weapons would often be unsuccessful in areas such as Iran.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] By the 16th century, cannons were made in a great variety of lengths and bore diameters, but the general rule was that the longer the barrel, the longer the range.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Some cannons made during this time had barrels exceeding 10 ft (3.0 m) in length, and could weigh up to 20,000 pounds (9,100 kg).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Consequently, large amounts of gunpowder were needed to allow them to fire stone balls several hundred yards.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] By mid-century, European monarchs began to classify cannons to reduce the confusion.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Henry II of France opted for six sizes of cannon, but others settled for more; the Spanish used twelve sizes, and the English sixteen.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] They are, from largest to smallest: the cannon royal, cannon, cannon serpentine, bastard cannon, demicannon, pedrero, culverin, basilisk, demiculverin, bastard culverin, saker, minion, falcon, falconet, serpentine, and rabinet.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Better powder had been developed by this time as well.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Instead of the finely ground powder used by the first bombards, powder was replaced by a "corned" variety of coarse grains.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] This coarse powder had pockets of air between grains, allowing fire to travel through and ignite the entire charge quickly and uniformly.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The end of the Middle Ages saw the construction of larger, more powerful cannon, as well as their spread throughout the world.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] As they were not effective at breaching the newer fortifications resulting from the development of cannon, siege engines—such as siege towers and trebuchets—became less widely used.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] However, wooden "battery-towers" took on a similar role as siege towers in the gunpowder age—such as that used at Siege of Kazan in 1552, which could hold ten large-calibre cannon, in addition to 50 lighter pieces.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Another notable effect of cannon on warfare during this period was the change in conventional fortifications.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Niccolò Machiavelli wrote, "There is no wall, whatever its thickness that artillery will not destroy in only a few days." Although castles were not immediately made obsolete by cannon, their use and importance on the battlefield rapidly declined.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Instead of majestic towers and merlons, the walls of new fortresses were thick, angled, and sloped, while towers became low and stout; increasing use was also made of earth and brick in breastworks and redoubts.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] These new defences became known as bastion forts, after their characteristic shape which attempted to force any advance towards it directly into the firing line of the guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] A few of these featured cannon batteries, such as the House of Tudor's Device Forts in England.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Bastion forts soon replaced castles in Europe and, eventually, those in the Americas as well.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] By the end of the 15th century, several technological advancements made cannons more mobile.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Wheeled gun carriages and trunnions became common, and the invention of the limber further facilitated transportation.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] As a result, field artillery became more viable and began to see more widespread use, often alongside the larger cannons intended for sieges.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Better gunpowder, cast-iron projectiles (replacing stone), and the standardisation of calibres meant that even relatively light cannons could be deadly.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Despite the increased maneuverability, however, cannon were still the slowest component of the army: a heavy English cannon required 23 horses to transport, while a culverin needed nine.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Even with this many animals pulling, they still moved at a walking pace.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Due to their relatively slow speed, lack of organisation, and undeveloped tactics, the combination of pike and shot still dominated the battlefields of Europe.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Innovations continued, notably the German invention of the mortar, a thick-walled, short-barrelled gun that blasted shot upward at a steep angle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Mortars were useful for sieges, as they could hit targets behind walls or other defences.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] This cannon found more use with the Dutch, who learnt to shoot bombs filled with powder from them.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] "Single firing" was first used to ignite the fuse, where the bomb was placed with the fuse down against the cannon's propellant.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] This often resulted in the fuse being blown into the bomb, causing it to blow up as it left the mortar.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Because of this, "double firing" was tried where the gunner lit the fuse and then the touch hole.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] This required considerable skill and timing, and was especially dangerous if the gun misfired, leaving a lighted bomb in the barrel.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Not until 1650 was it accidentally discovered that double-lighting was superfluous as the heat of firing would light the fuse.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden emphasised the use of light cannon and mobility in his army, and created new formations and tactics that revolutionised artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] He discontinued using all 12 pounder—or heavier—cannon as field artillery, preferring, instead, to use cannons that could be handled by only a few men.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] One obsolete type of gun, the "leatheren", was replaced by 4 pounder and 9 pounder demi-culverins.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] These could be operated by three men, and pulled by only two horses.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus's army was also the first to use a cartridge that contained both powder and shot which sped up reloading, increasing the rate of fire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Finally, against infantry he pioneered the use of canister shot—essentially a tin can filled with musket balls.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Until then there was no more than one cannon for every thousand infantrymen on the battlefield but Gustavus Adolphus increased the number of cannons sixfold.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Each regiment was assigned two pieces, though he often arranged them into batteries instead of distributing them piecemeal.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] He used these batteries to break his opponent's infantry line, while his cavalry would outflank their heavy guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Breitenfeld, in 1631, Adolphus proved the effectiveness of the changes made to his army, by defeating Johann Tserclaes, Count of Tilly.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Although severely outnumbered, the Swedes were able to fire between three and five times as many volleys of artillery, and their infantry's linear formations helped ensure they did not lose any ground.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Battered by cannon fire, and low on morale, Tilly's men broke ranks and fled.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] In England, cannons were being used to besiege various fortified buildings during the English Civil War.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Nathaniel Nye is recorded as testing a Birmingham cannon in 1643 and experimenting with a saker in 1645.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] From 1645 he was the master gunner to the Parliamentarian garrison at Evesham and in 1646 he successfully directed the artillery at the Siege of Worcester, detailing his experiences and in his 1647 book *The Art of Gunnery*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Believing that war was as much a science as an art, his explanations focused on triangulation, arithmetic, theoretical mathematics, and cartography as well as practical considerations such as the ideal specification for gunpowder or slow matches.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] His book acknowledged mathematicians such as Robert Recorde and Marcus Jordanus as well as earlier military writers on artillery such as Niccolò Fontana Tartaglia and Thomas (or Francis) Malthus (author of *A Treatise on Artificial Fire-Works*).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Around this time also came the idea of aiming the cannon to hit a target.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Gunners controlled the range of their cannons by measuring the angle of elevation, using a "gunner's quadrant".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannons did not have sights; therefore, even with measuring tools, aiming was still largely guesswork.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] In the latter half of the 17th century, the French engineer Sébastien Le Prestre de Vauban introduced a more systematic and scientific approach to attacking gunpowder fortresses, in a time when many field commanders "were notorious dunces in siegecraft".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Careful sapping forward, supported by enfilading ricochets, was a key feature of this system, and it even allowed Vauban to calculate the length of time a siege would take.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] He was also a prolific builder of bastion forts, and did much to popularize the idea of "depth in defence" in the face of cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] These principles were followed into the mid-19th century, when changes in armaments necessitated greater depth defence than Vauban had provided for.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] It was only in the years prior to World War I that new works began to break radically away from his designs.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The lower tier of 17th-century English ships of the line were usually equipped with demi-cannons, guns that fired a 32-pound (15 kg) solid shot, and could weigh up to 3,400 pounds (1,500 kg).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Demi-cannons were capable of firing these heavy metal balls with such force that they could penetrate more than a metre of solid oak, from a distance of 90 m (300 ft), and could dismast even the largest ships at close range.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Full cannon fired a 42-pound (19 kg) shot, but were discontinued by the 18th century, as they were too unwieldy.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] By the end of the 18th century, principles long adopted in Europe specified the characteristics of the Royal Navy's cannon, as well as the acceptable defects, and their severity.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The United States Navy tested guns by measuring them, firing them two or three times—termed "proof by powder"—and using pressurized water to detect leaks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The carronade was adopted by the Royal Navy in 1779; the lower muzzle velocity of the round shot when fired from this cannon was intended to create more wooden splinters when hitting the structure of an enemy vessel, as they were believed to be more deadly than the ball by itself.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The carronade was much shorter, and weighed between a third to a quarter of the equivalent long gun; for example, a 32-pounder carronade weighed less than a ton, compared with a 32-pounder long gun, which weighed over 3 t (3.0 long tons; 3.3 short tons).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The guns were, therefore, easier to handle, and also required less than half as much gunpowder, allowing fewer men to crew them.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Carronades were manufactured in the usual naval gun calibres, but were not counted in a ship of the line's rated number of guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] As a result, the classification of Royal Navy vessels in this period can be misleading, as they often carried more cannons than were listed.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannons were crucial in Napoleon's rise to power, and continued to play an important role in his army in later years.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] During the French Revolution, the unpopularity of the Directory led to riots and rebellions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] When over 25,000 royalists led by General Danican assaulted Paris, Paul Barras was appointed to defend the capital; outnumbered five to one and disorganised, the Republicans were desperate.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] When Napoleon arrived, he reorganised the defences but realised that without cannons the city could not be held.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] He ordered Joachim Murat to bring the guns from the Sablons artillery park; the Major and his cavalry fought their way to the recently captured cannons, and brought them back to Napoleon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] When Danican's poorly trained men attacked, on 13 Vendémiaire 1795 (5 October in the calendar used in France at the time), Napoleon ordered his cannon to fire grapeshot into the mob, an act that became known as the "whiff of grapeshot".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The slaughter effectively ended the threat to the new government, while, at the same time, making Bonaparte a famous—and popular—public figure.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Among the first generals to recognise that artillery was not being used to its full potential, Napoleon often massed his cannon into batteries and introduced several changes into the French artillery, improving it significantly and making it among the finest in Europe.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Such tactics were successfully used by the French, for example, at the Battle of Friedland, when 66 guns fired a total of 3,000 roundshot and 500 rounds of grapeshot, inflicting severe casualties to the Russian forces, whose losses numbered over 20,000 killed and wounded, in total.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Waterloo—Napoleon's final battle—the French army had many more artillery pieces than either the British or Prussians.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] As the battlefield was muddy, recoil caused cannons to bury themselves into the ground after firing, resulting in slow rates of fire, as more effort was required to move them back into an adequate firing position; also, roundshot did not ricochet with as much force from the wet earth.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Despite the drawbacks, sustained artillery fire proved deadly during the engagement, especially during the French cavalry attack.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The British infantry, having formed infantry squares, took heavy losses from the French guns, while their own cannons fired at the cuirassiers and lancers, when they fell back to regroup.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Eventually, the French ceased their assault, after taking heavy losses from the British cannon and musket fire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] In the 1810s and 1820s, greater emphasis was placed on the accuracy of long-range gunfire, and less on the weight of a broadside.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Around 1822, George Marshall wrote *Marshall's Practical Marine Gunnery*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The book was used by cannon operators in the United States Navy throughout the 19th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] It listed all the types of cannons and instructions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The carronade, although initially very successful and widely adopted, disappeared from the Royal Navy in the 1850s after the development of wrought-iron-jacketed steel cannon by William Armstrong and Joseph Whitworth.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Nevertheless, carronades were used in the American Civil War.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Western cannons during the 19th century became larger, more destructive, more accurate, and could fire at longer range.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] One example is the American 3-inch (76 mm) wrought-iron, muzzle-loading rifle, or Griffen gun (usually called the 3-inch Ordnance Rifle), used during the American Civil War, which had an effective range of over 1.1 mi (1.8 km).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Another is the smoothbore 12-pounder Napoleon, which originated in France in 1853 and was widely used by both sides in the American Civil War.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] This cannon was renowned for its sturdiness, reliability, firepower, flexibility, relatively lightweight, and range of 1,700 m (5,600 ft).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The practice of rifling—casting spiralling lines inside the cannon's barrel—was applied to artillery more frequently by 1855, as it gave cannon projectiles gyroscopic stability, which improved their accuracy.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] One of the earliest rifled cannons was the breech-loading Armstrong Gun—also invented by William Armstrong—which boasted significantly improved range, accuracy, and power than earlier weapons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The projectile fired from the Armstrong gun could reportedly pierce through a ship's side and explode inside the enemy vessel, causing increased damage and casualties.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The British military adopted the Armstrong gun, and was impressed; the Duke of Cambridge even declared that it "could do everything but speak".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Despite being significantly more advanced than its predecessors, the Armstrong gun was rejected soon after its integration, in favour of the muzzle-loading pieces that had been in use before.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] While both types of gun were effective against wooden ships, neither had the capability to pierce the armour of ironclads; due to reports of slight problems with the breeches of the Armstrong gun, and their higher cost, the older muzzle-loaders were selected to remain in service instead.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The superior cannon of the Western world brought them tremendous advantages in warfare.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] For example, in the First Opium War in China, during the 19th century, British battleships bombarded the coastal areas and fortifications from afar, safe from the reach of the Chinese cannons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Similarly, the shortest war in recorded history, the Anglo-Zanzibar War of 1896, was brought to a swift conclusion by shelling from British cruisers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannons in the 20th and 21st centuries are usually divided into sub-categories and given separate names.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Some of the most widely used types of modern cannon are howitzers, mortars, guns, and autocannon, although a few very large-calibre cannon, custom-designed, have also been constructed.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Nuclear artillery was experimented with, but was abandoned as impractical.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Modern artillery is used in a variety of roles, depending on its type.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] According to NATO, the general role of artillery is to provide fire support, which is defined as "the application of fire, coordinated with the manoeuvre of forces to destroy, neutralize, or suppress the enemy".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] When referring to cannons, the term *gun* is often used incorrectly.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] By the early 20th century, infantry weapons had become more powerful, forcing most artillery away from the front lines.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Despite the change to indirect fire, cannons proved highly effective during World War I, directly or indirectly causing over 75% of casualties.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The onset of trench warfare after the first few months of World War I greatly increased the demand for howitzers, as they were more suited to hitting targets in trenches.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Furthermore, their shells carried more explosives than those of guns, and caused considerably less barrel wear.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The German army had the advantage here as they began the war with many more howitzers than the French.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] World War I also saw the use of the Paris Gun, the longest-ranged gun ever fired.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] This 200 mm (8 in) calibre gun was used by the Germans against Paris and could hit targets more than 122 km (76 mi) away.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The Second World War sparked new developments in cannon technology.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Among them were sabot rounds, hollow-charge projectiles, and proximity fuses, all of which increased the effectiveness of cannon against specific targets.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The proximity fuse emerged on the battlefields of Europe in late December 1944.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Used to great effect in anti-aircraft projectiles, proximity fuses were fielded in both the European and Pacific Theatres of Operations; they were particularly useful against V-1 flying bombs and kamikaze planes.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Although widely used in naval warfare, and in anti-air guns, both the British and Americans feared unexploded proximity fuses would be reverse engineered, leading to them limiting their use in continental battles.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] During the Battle of the Bulge, however, the fuses became known as the American artillery's "Christmas present" for the German army because of their effectiveness against German personnel in the open, when they frequently dispersed attacks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Anti-tank guns were also tremendously improved during the war: in 1939, the British used primarily 2 pounder and 6 pounder guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] By the end of the war, 17 pounders had proven much more effective against German tanks, and 32 pounders had entered development.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Meanwhile, German tanks were continuously upgraded with better main guns, in addition to other improvements.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] For example, the Panzer III was originally designed with a 37 mm gun, but was mass-produced with a 50 mm cannon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] To counter the threat of the Russian T-34s, another, more powerful 50 mm gun was introduced, only to give way to a larger 75 mm cannon, which was in a fixed mount as the StuG III, the most-produced German World War II armoured fighting vehicle of any type.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Despite the improved guns, production of the Panzer III was ended in 1943, as the tank still could not match the T-34, and was replaced by the Panzer IV and Panther tanks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] In 1944, the 8.8 cm KwK 43 and many variations, entered service with the Wehrmacht, and was used as both a tank main gun, and as the PaK 43 anti-tank gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful guns to see service in World War II, it was capable of destroying any Allied tank at very long ranges.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Despite being designed to fire at trajectories with a steep angle of descent, howitzers can be fired directly, as was done by the 11th Marine Regiment at the Battle of Chosin Reservoir, during the Korean War.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Two field batteries fired directly upon a battalion of Chinese infantry; the Marines were forced to brace themselves against their howitzers, as they had no time to dig them in.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The Chinese infantry took heavy casualties, and were forced to retreat.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The tendency to create larger calibre cannons during the World Wars has reversed since.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The United States Army, for example, sought a lighter, more versatile howitzer, to replace their aging pieces.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] As it could be towed, the M198 was selected to be the successor to the World War II–era cannons used at the time, and entered service in 1979.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Still in use today, the M198 is, in turn, being slowly replaced by the M777 Ultralightweight howitzer, which weighs nearly half as much and can be more easily moved.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Although land-based artillery such as the M198 are powerful, long-ranged, and accurate, naval guns have not been neglected, despite being much smaller than in the past, and, in some cases, having been replaced by cruise missiles.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] However, the *Zumwalt*-class destroyer's planned armament included the Advanced Gun System (AGS), a pair of 155 mm guns, which fire the Long Range Land-Attack Projectile.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The warhead, which weighed 24 pounds (11 kg), had a circular error of probability of 50 m (160 ft), and was mounted on a rocket, to increase the effective range to 100 nmi (190 km), further than that of the Paris Gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The AGS's barrels would be water-cooled, and fire 10 rounds per minute, per gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The combined firepower from both turrets would give a *Zumwalt*-class destroyer the firepower equivalent to 12 conventional M198 howitzers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The reason for the re-integration of cannons as a main armament in United States Navy ships was because satellite-guided munitions fired from a gun would be less expensive than a cruise missile but have a similar guidance capability.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Autocannons automatically fire a series of projectiles, similarly to a machine gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] They have mechanisms to automatically load their ammunition, and have a high rate of fire often approaching, or, in the case of rotary autocannons, even surpassing the firing rate of a machine gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Autocannons are usually of larger calibre than machine guns, typically 20 mm (0.8 in) or greater, and can usually fire explosive shells, unlike machine guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Explosive ammunition weighing less than 400 grams, as used by machine-gun calibres, is additionally banned in international conflict for parties to the Saint Petersburg Declaration of 1868.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Most nations use rapid-fire cannon on light vehicles, instead of a more powerful, but heavier, tank gun with a low rate of fire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] A typical autocannon is the 25 mm US "Bushmaster" chain gun, mounted on the LAV-25 and M2 Bradley armoured vehicles.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The typical rate of fire for a modern autocannon ranges from 90 to 1,800 rounds per minute; systems with multiple barrels, such as rotary autocannon, can have rates of fire of several thousand rounds per minute.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The fastest of these is the GSh-6-23, which has a rate of fire of over 10,000 rounds per minute.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Autocannons are often fitted in aircraft and as shipboard anti-aircraft weapons, as they provide greater destructive power than previously-used machine guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The first documented installation of a cannon firing explosive shells on an aircraft was on the Voisin Canon in 1911, displayed at the Paris Exposition that year.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] By World War I, all of the major powers were experimenting with aircraft-mounted cannons; however, their low rate of fire and great size and weight precluded any of them from being anything other than experimental.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The most successful (or least unsuccessful) was the SPAD 12 Ca.1 single-seat fighter with a single 37 mm Puteaux mounted to fire between the cylinder banks and through the propeller boss of the aircraft's Hispano-Suiza 8C engine.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The pilot (by necessity an ace) had to manually load one round at a time.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The first autocannon were developed during World War I as anti-aircraft guns, and one of these, the Coventry Ordnance Works "COW 37 mm gun", was installed in an aircraft.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] However, the war ended before it could be given a field trial, and it never became standard equipment in a production aircraft.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Later trials had it fixed at a steep angle upwards in both the Vickers Type 161 and the Westland C.O.W.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Gun Fighter, an idea that returned later.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] During this period autocannons became available, and several fighters of the German *Luftwaffe* and the Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service were fitted with 20 mm cannons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] They continued to be installed as an adjunct to machine guns rather than as a replacement, as the rate of fire was too low and each gun was too heavy.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] There was some debate in the RAF as to whether the greater number of possible rounds being fired from a machine gun, or a smaller number of explosive rounds from a cannon was preferable.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Improvements during the war in regards to rate of fire allowed the cannon to displace the machine gun almost entirely.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannons were more effective than machine-guns against armour, so they came increasingly into use in World War II; newer fighter aircraft such as the Hawker Tempest usually carried two or four instead of the six to twelve machine guns of earlier aircraft.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The Hispano-Suiza HS.404, Oerlikon 20 mm cannon, MG FF, and their numerous variants became among the most widely used autocannon in the war.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Aircraft cannons, as with machine guns, were either fixed to fire forwards (mounted in the wings, in the nose or fuselage, or in a pannier under either), typically on manoeuvrable fighters, or mounted movably in manned gun turrets on heavier less agile aircraft such as bombers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Both the Germans and Japanese mounted cannons to fire upwards and forwards for use against heavy bombers, with the Germans calling guns so-installed *Schräge Musik*, derived from a German colloquialism for jazz music—*schräg* means "off-key".
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Nearly all modern fighter aircraft are armed with an autocannon, and they are also commonly fitted on ground-attack aircraft.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful examples is the 30mm GAU-8/A Avenger Gatling-type rotary cannon mounted on the Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The Lockheed AC-130 gunship, based on a transport aircraft, can carry a 105 mm howitzer and a variety of autocannons ranging up to 40 mm.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Both are used in the close air support role.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannons in general have the form of a truncated cone with an internal cylindrical bore for holding an explosive charge and a projectile.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The thickest, strongest, and closed part of the cone is located near the explosive charge.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] As any explosive charge will dissipate in all directions equally, the thickest portion of the cannon is useful for containing and directing this force.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Field artillery cannon in Europe and the Americas were initially made most often of bronze, though later forms were constructed of cast iron and eventually steel.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] However, cast-iron cannon have a tendency to burst without having shown any previous weakness or wear, and this makes them more dangerous to operate.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The older and more-stable forms of cannon were muzzle-loading as opposed to breech-loading—to be used they had to have their ordnance packed down the bore through the muzzle rather than inserted through the breech.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The following terms refer to the components or aspects of a classical western cannon (c.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] In what follows, the words *near*, *close*, and *behind* will refer to those parts towards the thick, closed end of the piece, and *far*, *front*, *in front of*, and *before* to the thinner, open end.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] is determined by the diameter of its bore.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] made of copper screwed into the length of the vent.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The main body of a cannon consists of three basic extensions: the foremost and the longest is called the *chase*, the middle portion is the *reinforce*, and the closest and briefest portion is the *cascabel* or *cascable*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The chase is simply the entire conical part of the cannon in front of the *reinforce*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] the narrowest part of the chase, always located near the foremost end of the piece.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] these are a second series of such rings located at the near end of the chase.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] To pack a muzzle-loading cannon, first gunpowder is poured down the bore.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] This is followed by a layer of wadding (often nothing more than paper), and then the cannonball itself.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] A certain amount of windage (in this case meaning that the bore is designed slightly wider than the cannonball) allows the ball to fit down the bore, though the greater the windage the less efficient the propulsion of the ball when the gunpowder is ignited.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] To fire the cannon, the fuse located in the vent is lit, quickly burning down to the gunpowder, which then explodes violently, propelling wadding and ball down the bore and out of the muzzle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] A small portion of exploding gas also escapes through the vent, but this does not dramatically affect the total force exerted on the ball.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] *Gun* in this context specifically refers to a type of cannon that fires projectiles at high speeds, and usually at relatively low angles; they have been used in warships, and as field artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The term *cannon* is also used for autocannon, a modern repeating weapon firing explosive projectiles.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannon have been used extensively in fighter aircraft since World War II.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] In the 1770s, cannon operation worked as follows: each cannon would be manned by two gunners, six soldiers, and four officers of artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The right gunner was to prime the piece and load it with powder, and the left gunner would fetch the powder from the magazine and be ready to fire the cannon at the officer's command.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] On each side of the cannon, three soldiers stood, to ram and sponge the cannon, and hold the ladle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The second soldier on the left was tasked with providing 50 bullets.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Before loading, the cannon would be cleaned with a wet sponge to extinguish any smouldering material from the last shot.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Fresh powder could be set off prematurely by lingering ignition sources.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The powder was added, followed by wadding of paper or hay, and the ball was placed in and rammed down.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] After ramming, the cannon would be aimed with the elevation set using a quadrant and a plummet.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] At 45 degrees, the ball had the utmost range: about ten times the gun's level range.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Any angle above a horizontal line was called random-shot.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Wet sponges were used to cool the pieces every ten or twelve rounds.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] During the Napoleonic Wars, a British gun team consisted of five gunners to aim it, clean the bore with a damp sponge to quench any remaining embers before a fresh charge was introduced, and another to load the gun with a bag of powder and then the projectile.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The fourth gunner pressed his thumb on the vent hole, to prevent a draught that might fan a flame.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The charge loaded, the fourth would prick the bagged charge through the vent hole, and fill the vent with powder.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] On command, the fifth gunner would fire the piece with a slow match.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Friction primers replaced slow match ignition by the mid-19th century.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] When a cannon had to be abandoned such as in a retreat or surrender, the touch hole of the cannon would be plugged flush with an iron spike, disabling the cannon (at least until metal boring tools could be used to remove the plug).
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] A gun was said to be *honeycombed* when the surface of the bore had cavities, or holes in it, caused by corrosion or casting defects.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] In the United States, muzzleloading cannons made before 1899 (and replicas) that are unable to fire fixed ammunition are considered antiques.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] They are not subject to the Gun Control Act of 1968 or National Firearms Act of 1934.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] They may be subject to local rules in some jurisdictions, however.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Historically, logs or poles have been used as decoys to mislead the enemy as to the strength of an emplacement.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The "Quaker Gun trick" was used by Colonel William Washington's Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War; in 1780, approximately 100 Loyalists surrendered to them, rather than face bombardment.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] During the American Civil War, Quaker guns were also used by the Confederates, to compensate for their shortage of artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The decoy cannon were painted black at the "muzzle", and positioned behind fortifications to delay Union attacks on those positions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] On occasion, real gun carriages were used to complete the deception.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannon sounds have sometimes been used in classical pieces with a military theme.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] One of the best known examples is Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky's *1812 Overture*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The overture is to be performed using an artillery section together with the orchestra, resulting in noise levels high enough that musicians are required to wear ear protection.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The cannon fire simulates Russian artillery bombardments of the Battle of Borodino, a critical battle in Napoleon's invasion of Russia, whose defeat the piece celebrates.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] When the overture was first performed, the cannon were fired by an electric current triggered by the conductor.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] However, the overture was not recorded with real cannon fire until Mercury Records and conductor Antal Doráti's 1958 recording of the Minnesota Orchestra.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannon fire is also frequently used in presentations of the *1812* on American Independence Day, a tradition started by Arthur Fiedler of the Boston Pops in 1974.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The hard rock band AC/DC used cannon fire in their song "For Those About to Rock (We Salute You)", and in live shows replica Napoleonic cannons and pyrotechnics were used to perform the piece.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] A recording of that song has accompanied the firing of an authentic reproduction of a M1857 12-pounder Napoleon during Columbus Blue Jackets goal celebrations at Nationwide Arena since opening night of the 2007–08 season.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The cannon is the focal point of the team's alternate logo on its third jerseys.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannons have been fired in touchdown celebrations by several American football teams including the San Diego Chargers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The Pittsburgh Steelers used one only during the 1962 campaign but discontinued it after Buddy Dial was startled by inadvertently running face-first into the cannon's smoky discharge in a 42–27 loss to the Dallas Cowboys.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannon recovered from the sea are often extensively damaged from exposure to salt water; electrolytic reduction treatment is required to forestall corrosion.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] The cannon is then washed in deionized water to remove the electrolyte, and is treated in tannic acid, which prevents further rust and gives the metal a bluish-black colour.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] Cannon on display may be protected from oxygen and moisture by a wax sealant.
[src:carabine-à-tige/cannon-p02] A coat of polyurethane may also be painted over the wax sealant, to prevent the cannon from attracting dust.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The **French 75 mm field gun** is a quick-firing field artillery piece adopted in March 1898.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Its official French designation was: **Canon de 75 mm Mle 1897**.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] It was commonly known as the **French 75**, simply the **75** and **Soixante-Quinze** (French for "seventy-five").
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French 75 was designed as an anti-personnel weapon system for delivering large volumes of time-fused shrapnel shells on enemy troops advancing in the open.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] After 1915 and the onset of trench warfare, impact-detonated high-explosive shells prevailed.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] By 1918, the 75 became the main agents of delivery for toxic gas shells.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The 75s also became widely used as truck mounted anti-aircraft artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] They were the main armament of the Saint-Chamond tank in 1918 and the Char 2C.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French 75 is widely regarded as the first modern artillery piece.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] It was the first field gun to include a hydro-pneumatic recoil mechanism, which kept the gun's trail and wheels perfectly still during the firing sequence.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Since it did not need to be re-aimed after each shot, the crew could reload and fire as soon as the barrel returned to its resting position.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In typical use, the French 75 could deliver fifteen rounds per minute on its target, either shrapnel or melinite high-explosive, up to about 8,500 m (5.3 mi) away.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Its firing rate could even reach close to 30 rounds per minute, albeit only for a very short time and with a highly experienced crew.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] At the opening of World War I, in 1914, the French Army had about 4,000 of these field guns in service.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] By the end of the war, about 12,000 had been produced.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] It was also in service with the American Expeditionary Forces, which had been supplied with about 2,000 French 75 field guns.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Several thousand were still in use in the French Army at the opening of World War II, updated with new wheels and tires to allow towing by trucks rather than by horses.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French 75 set the pattern for almost all early-20th century field pieces, with guns of mostly 75 mm forming the basis of many field artillery units into the early stages of World War II.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The forerunner of the French 75 was an experimental 57 mm gun that was first assembled in September 1891 at the Bourges arsenal under the direction of Captain Sainte-Claire Deville.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Self-contained ammunition, with the powder charge in a brass case which also held the shell.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] An early hydro-pneumatic short recoil mechanism that was designed by Major Louis Baquet.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A rotating screw breech built under license from Thorsten Nordenfelt.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The only major design difference between the 57 and 75 that would emerge was the recoil system.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] But, in 1890, even before the 57 entered testing, General Mathieu, Director of Artillery at the Ministry of War, had been informed that Konrad Haussner, a German engineer working at the Ingolstadt arsenal, had patented an oil-and-compressed-air long-recoil system.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] They also learned that Krupp was considering introducing the system after testing it.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Krupp would later reject Haussner's invention, due to unsolvable technical problems caused by hydraulic fluid leakage.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In 1891, Haussner sold his patents to a firm named Gruson, which searched for potential buyers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] After reviewing the blueprints in February 1892, the French artillery engineers advised that a gun should be produced without purchasing the Haussner invention.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Accordingly, General Mathieu turned to Lt.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Colonel Joseph-Albert Deport, at the time the Director of the Atelier de Construction de Puteaux (APX), and asked him whether he could construct a gun on the general principle of the Haussner long-cylinder recoil without infringing the existing patents.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] After it was judged possible, a formal request was sent out on 13 July 1892.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] It took five more years under the overall leadership of Mathieu's successor, General Deloye, to perfect and finally adopt in March 1898 an improved and final version of the Deport 75 mm long-recoil field gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Various deceptions, some of them linked to the Dreyfus Case which erupted in 1894, had been implemented by Deloye and French counter-intelligence to distract German espionage.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The final experimental version of Deport's 75 mm field gun was tested during the summer of 1894 and judged very promising.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Extensive trials, however, revealed that it was still prone to hydraulic fluid leakage from the long-recoil mechanism.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The Deport 75 was returned to Puteaux arsenal for further improvements.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Hydraulic fluid leakage was typical of this experimental phase of artillery development during the 1890s, as Haussner and Krupp had previously experienced.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In December 1894, Deport was passed over for promotion, and resigned to join "Chatillon-Commentry", a private armaments firm.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Two young military engineers from Ecole Polytechnique, Captains Etienne Sainte-Claire Deville and Emile Rimailho, continued development and introduced an improved version in 1896.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Their contribution was a leakproof hydro-pneumatic long-recoil mechanism which they named "Frein II" (Brake # II).
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A major improvement was the placement of improved silver-alloy rings on the freely moving piston which separated the compressed air and the hydraulic fluid inside the main hydro-pneumatic recoil cylinder.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] These and other modifications achieved the desired result: the long-term retention of hydraulic fluid and compressed air inside the recoil system, even under the worst field conditions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Captain Sainte-Claire Deville also designed important additional features, such as a device for piercing the fuzes of shrapnel shells automatically during the firing sequence (an "automatic fuze-setter"), thus selecting the desired bursting distance.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The independent sight had also been perfected for easy field use by the crews, and a nickel-steel shield was added to protect the gunners.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The armored caissons were designed to be tilted in order to present the shells horizontally to the crews.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The wheel brakes could be swung under each wheel ("abattage"), and, together with the trail spade, they immobilized the gun during firing.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The gun was officially adopted on 28 March 1898 under the name "***Matériel de* 75 mm *Mle 1*897**".
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The public saw it for the first time during the Bastille Day parade of 14 July 1899.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The gun's barrel slid back on rollers, including a set at the muzzle, when the shot was fired.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The barrel was attached near the breech to a piston rod extending into an oil-filled cylinder placed just underneath the gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] When the barrel recoiled, the piston was pulled back by the barrel's recoil and thus pushed the oil through a small orifice and into a second cylinder placed underneath.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] That second cylinder contained a freely floating piston which separated the surging oil from a confined volume of compressed air.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] During the barrel's recoil, the floating piston was forced forward by the oil, compressing the air even further.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] This action absorbed the recoil progressively as the internal air pressure rose and, at the end of recoil, generated a strong but decreasing back pressure that returned the gun forward to its original position.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The smoothness of this system had no equal in 1897, and for at least another ten years.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Each recoil cycle on the French 75, including the return forward, lasted about two seconds, permitting a maximum theoretical firing rate of about 30 rounds per minute.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] At the beginning in 1914, the French 75 fired two main types of shells, both with high muzzle velocities (535 m/s for the shrapnel shell) and a maximum range of 8,500 metres.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Their relatively flat trajectories extended all the way to the designated targets.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] French 75 shells, at least initially in 1914, were essentially anti-personnel.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] They had been designed for the specific purpose of inflicting maximum casualties on enemy troops stationing or advancing in the open.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Several new shells and fuses were introduced due to the demands of trench warfare.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In 1918, a boat-tailed shell (with a superior ballistic coefficient) which could reach 11,000 metres (12,000 yd) was deployed for use during the latter part of the war.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Developed through French artillery research, it increased the effective range of the French 75 by about thirty-eight percent.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Every shell, whether it be a high-explosive or shrapnel shell, was fixed to a brass case which was ejected when the breech was manually opened.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Semi-automatic breech opening and shell ejection during recoil and return had not been developed yet.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French 75 introduced a new concept in artillery technology: rapid firing without realigning the gun after each shot.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Older artillery had to be resighted after each shot in order to stay on target, and thus fired no more than two aimed shots per minute.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French 75 easily delivered fifteen aimed rounds per minute and could fire even faster for short periods of time, but the long-term sustained rate was 3-4 rounds per minute as more than this would overheat the barrel.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] This rate of fire, the gun's accuracy, and the lethality of the ammunition against personnel, made the French 75 superior to all other regimental field artillery at the time.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] When made ready for action, the first shot buried the trail spade and the two wheel anchors into the ground, following which all other shots were fired from a stable platform.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Bringing down the wheel anchors tied to the braking system was called "*abattage*".
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The gun could not be elevated beyond eighteen degrees, unless the trail spade had been deeply dug into the ground; however, the 75 mm field gun was not designed for plunging fire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The gun could be traversed laterally 3 degrees to the sides by sliding the trail on the wheel's axle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Progressive traversing together with small changes in elevation could be carried out while continuously firing, called "*fauchage*" or "sweeping fire".
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A four-gun battery firing shrapnel could deliver 17,000 ball projectiles over an area 100 metres wide by 400 metres long in a single minute, with devastating results.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Because of the gun's traversing ability, the greater the distance to the enemy concentration, the wider the area that could be swept.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Each Mle 1897 75 mm field gun battery of four guns consisted of 170 men led by four officers recruited among graduates of engineering schools.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Enlisted men from the countryside were given charge of the six horses that pulled each gun and its first limber.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Another six horses pulled each additional limber and caisson that were assigned to each gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A battery included 160 horses, most of them pulling ammunition as well as repair and supply caissons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French artillery entered the war in August 1914 with more than 4,000 Mle 1897 75 mm field guns (1,000 batteries of four guns each).
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Over 17,500 Mle 1897 75 mm field guns were produced during World War I, over and above the 4,100 French 75s which were already deployed by the French Army in August 1914.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] All the essential parts, including the gun's barrel and the oleo-pneumatic recoil mechanisms were manufactured by French State arsenals: Puteaux, Bourges, Châtellerault and St Etienne.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A truck-mounted anti-aircraft version of the French 75 was assembled by the automobile firm of De Dion-Bouton and adopted in 1913.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The total production of 75 mm shells during World War I exceeded 200 million rounds, mostly by private industry.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In order to increase shell production from 20,000 rounds per day to 100,000 in 1915, the government turned to civilian contractors, and, as a result, shell quality deteriorated.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] This led to an epidemic of burst barrels which afflicted 75 mm artillery during 1915.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Colonel Sainte-Claire Deville corrected the problem, which was due to microfissures in the bases of the shells, due to shortcuts in manufacturing.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Shell quality was restored by September 1915, but never to the full exacting standards of pre-war manufacture.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French 75 was considered the best field gun of the war.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] It gave its best performances during the Battle of the Marne in August–September 1914 and at Verdun in 1916.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] At the time, the contribution of 75 mm artillery to these military successes, and thus to the French victories that ensued, was seen as significant.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In the case of Verdun, over 1,000 French 75s (250 batteries) were constantly in action, night and day, on the battlefield during a period of nearly nine months.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French 75 was a devastating anti-personnel weapon against waves of infantry attacking in the open, as at the Marne and Verdun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] However, its shells were comparatively light and lacked the power to obliterate trench works, concrete bunkers and deeply buried shelters.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Thus, with time, the French 75 batteries became routinely used to cut corridors with high-explosive shells, across the belts of German barbed wire.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] After 1916, the 75 batteries became the carriers of choice to deliver toxic gas shells, including mustard gas and phosgene.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The French Army had to wait until early 1917 to receive in numbers fast-firing heavy artillery equipped with hydraulic recoil brakes (e.g. the 155 mm Schneider howitzer and the long-range Canon de 155 mm GPF).
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In the meantime, it had to make do with about four thousand de Bange 90 mm, 120 mm and 155 mm field and converted fortress guns, all without recoil brakes, that were effective but inferior in rate of fire to the more modern German heavy artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] During the interwar period, the French army kept the Mle 1897 in service and it continued to be the main gun of the French field artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The surplus guns were soon sold to allied countries.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Upgrades were considered in the 1920s, such as the use of a split trail carriages.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The prototypes were satisfactory but the French Army decided not to fund the improvements, choosing instead to develop a new model.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] That new plan was abandoned after the 1920s budget cuts.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] However, a few Mle 1897 guns were modernized between the wars.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The Rif War showed the vulnerability of the crew against snipers during guerilla operations.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The *roues métalliques DAG*, solid metallic wheels, were developed in the late 1920s to offer more protection to the crew, although they were very noisy during movements.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] They were mostly sent to units serving in the North African colonies.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] From 1928, the French Army also adopted bogies to enable transport by motor vehicles, such as the Citroën-Kégresse P17.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Mounted on the bogies, the guns could be towed at a maximum speed of 30 km/h on the road but the removal of the bogies was complicated.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A more modern version of the Mle 1897, the *Canon de 75 Mle 1897/33*, mounted the original barrel and recoil mechanism on a new split-trail carriage.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In addition to the new carriage the Mle 1897/33 had a new gun shield, pneumatic tires, sprung suspension, and the wheels "toed in" when the trails were spread.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The new carriage offered higher angles of traverse and elevation than the earlier box-trail carriage.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] However, the Mle 1897/33 was inferior to the new *Canon de 105 C Mle 1935 B* that used the same carriage, so it was only built in small numbers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A more modest upgrade to the Mle 1897 was the *Canon de 75 Mle 1897/38*, which was a modernized field artillery variant.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The original box-trail carriage was retained but the gun had a new gun shield, sprung suspension and pneumatic tires for motor transport.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The 75 Mle 1897 was also considered as a possible anti-tank gun by the French Army, who in 1936 ordered a new circular platform, the *plateforme Arbel Mle 1935*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Mounted on that platform, the Mle 1897 gun could now quickly traverse to engage enemy tanks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] During this period, a number of the guns entered Irish service, being sourced from Britain.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Despite obsolescence brought on by new developments in artillery design, large numbers of 75s were still in use in 1939 (4,500 in the French Army alone), and they eventually found their way into a number of unlikely places.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] A substantial number had been delivered to Poland in 1919–20, together with infantry ordnance, in order to fight in the Polish-Soviet War.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] They were known as *75 mm armata wz.1897*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In 1939 the Polish army had 1,374 of these guns, making it by far the most numerous artillery piece in Polish service.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Many were captured by Germany during the Fall of France in 1940, in addition to Polish guns captured in 1939.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Over 3,500 were modified with a muzzle brake and mounted on a 5 cm Pak 38 carriage, now named 7.5 cm Pak 97/38 they were used by the Wehrmacht in 1942 as an emergency weapon against the Soviet Union's T-34 and KV tanks.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Its relatively low velocity and a lack of modern armor-piercing ammunition limited its effectiveness as an anti-tank weapon.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] When the German 7.5 cm Pak 40 became available in sufficient numbers, most remaining Pak 97/38 pieces were returned to occupied France to reinforce the Atlantic Wall defenses or were supplied to Axis nations like Romania (PAK 97/38) and Hungary.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Non-modified remainders were used as second-line and coastal artillery pieces under the German designation *7.5 cm FK 231(f)* and *7,5 cm FK 97(p)*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The few 60 Mle 1897/33s captured by the Germans were given the designation *7.5 cm K232(f)*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In 1915, Britain acquired a number of "autocanon de 75 mm mle 1913" anti-aircraft guns, as a stopgap measure while it developed its own anti-aircraft alternatives.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] They were used in the defence of Britain, usually mounted on de Dion motor lorries using the French mounting, which the British referred to as the "Breech Trunnion".
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Britain also purchased a number of the standard 75 mm guns and adapted them for AA use using a Coventry Ordnance Works mounting, the "Centre Trunnion".
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] At the Armistice, there were 29 guns in service in Britain.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In June 1940, with many British field guns lost in the Battle of France, 895 M1897 field guns and a million rounds of ammunition were purchased from the U.S.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] For political purposes, the sale to the British Purchasing Commission was made through the US Steel Corporation.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The basic, unmodified gun was known in British service as "Ordnance, QF, 75 mm Mk 1", although many of the guns were issued to units on converted or updated mountings.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] They were operated by field artillery and anti-tank units.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Some of the guns had their wheels and part of their carriages cut away so that they could be mounted on a pedestal called a "Mounting, 75 mm Mk 1".
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] These weapons were employed as light coastal artillery and were not declared obsolete until March 1945.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] During World War II, through Lend Lease, the British received 170 American half-track M3 gun motor carriage, which mounted a 75 mm; they used these in Italy and Northern Europe until the end of the war as fire-support vehicles in armoured car regiments.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Romania had a considerable number of World War I guns of 75 mm and 76.2 mm.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Some models were modernized at Resita works in 1935 including French md.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The upgrade was made with removable barrels.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Several types of guns of close caliber were barreled to use the best ammunition available for 75 mm caliber, explosive projectile model 1917 "Schneider".
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The new barrel was made of steel alloy with chrome and nickel with excellent mechanical resistance to pressure which allowed, after modifying the firing brake, the recovery arch and the sighting devices an increase of the range from 8.5 km to 11.2 km and a rate of fire of 20 rounds/minute.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] These upgraded field guns were used in all infantry divisions in World War II, additionally these guns also used Costinescu 75 mm anti-tank round.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Army adopted the French 75 mm field gun during World War I and used it extensively in battle.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The U.S. designation of the basic weapon was **75 mm Gun M1897**.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] There were 480 American 75 mm field gun batteries (over 1,900 guns) on the battlefields of France in November 1918.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Manufacture of the French 75 by American industry began in the spring of 1918 and quickly built up to an accelerated pace.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Carriages were built by Willys-Overland, the hydro-pneumatic recuperators by Singer Manufacturing Company and Rock Island Arsenal, the cannon itself by Symington-Anderson and Wisconsin Gun Company.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] American industry built 1,050 French 75s during World War I, but only 143 had been shipped to France by 11 November 1918; most American batteries used French-built 75s in action.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The first U.S. artillery shots in action in World War I were fired by Battery C, 6th Field Artillery on October 23, 1917, with a French 75 named "Bridget" which is preserved today at the United States Army Ordnance Museum.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] During his service with the American Expeditionary Forces, Captain (and future U.S.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Truman commanded a battery of French 75s.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] By the early 1930s, the only U.S. artillery units that remained horse-drawn were those assigned to infantry and cavalry divisions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Along with new ammunition, these features increased the effective range and allowed the gun to be used as an anti-tank gun, in which form it equipped the first tank destroyer battalions.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] In 1941, these guns began to become surplus when they were gradually being replaced by the M2A1 105 mm M101 split-trail Howitzer; some were removed from their towed carriages and installed on the M3 Half-Track as the M3 gun motor carriage (GMC) tank destroyers.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] However, equipment shortages led to the M1897s remaining in the inventory of U.S.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Army units in the Philippine Islands as well as in artillery units of the Philippine Army as of December 1941, and they would be used in action against the Japanese before the Allied forces in the Philippines surrendered in May 1942.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] M3 GMCs were used in the Pacific theater during the Battle for the Philippines and by Marine Regimental Weapons Companies until 1944.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The M3 GMC also formed the equipment of the early American tank destroyer battalions during operations in North Africa and Italy, and continued in use with the British in Italy and in small numbers in Northern Europe until the end of the war.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] Many others were used for training until 1942.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The 75 mm M2 and M3 tank guns of the M3 Lee and M4 Sherman Medium tanks, the 75 mm M6 tank gun of the M24 Chaffee light tank and the 75 mm gun of the -G and -H subtypes of the B-25 Mitchell bomber all used the same ammunition as the M1897.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The 75 mm Pack Howitzer M1 used the same projectiles fired from a smaller 75×272R case.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] After World War II, the Canon de 75 modèle 1897 remained in service or kept in reserve with a few countries in Africa, Asia, and Latin America including: Cameroon, Cambodia, Laos, Mexico, Morocco, and Upper Volta (modern Burkina Faso) as late as 1977.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The gun is still used in France as a saluting gun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] When the French Army discarded its 105 HM2 howitzers to replace them with MO-120-RT mortars, only 155 mm artillery pieces remained, for which no blank cartridges were available.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The Army therefore recommissioned two Canon de 75 modèle 1897, then located at the Musée de l'Artillerie de Draguignan.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The **75 mm modèle 1897–1915** was placed on *SMCA modèle 1925* mountings with a vertical elevation of -10 to +70° and a 360° rotation.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] This allowed it to be used in an anti-aircraft role.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] New 75 mm guns were developed specifically for anti-aircraft use.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-de-75-modèle-1897] The **75 mm modèle 1922**, **75 mm modèle 1924** and **75 mm modèle 1927** of 50 calibre were developed from the 62.5 calibre '75 mm Schneider modèle 1908' mounted on the Danton-class battleships.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The **Canon obusier de 12** (officially the "Canon obusier de campagne de 12 livres, modèle 1853"), also known as the **"Canon de l’Empereur"** ("emperor's cannon"), was a type of canon-obusier (literally "shell-gun cannon", "gun-howitzer") developed by France in 1853.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] Its performance and versatility (it was able to fire either ball, shell, canister or grapeshot) allowed it to replace all the previous field guns, especially the Canon de 8 and the Canon de 12 as well as the two howitzers of the Valée system.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The cannon was known in the United States as the **12-pounder Napoleon** after French President and Emperor Napoleon III.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The *"canon obusier"* was a smoothbore cannon firing either shells, balls, or canister.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] This was an improvement over previous cannon firing only balls, such as those of the Gribeauval system.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The new weapon "revolutionized field artillery.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The Napoleon was light enough to be moved rapidly on the battlefield by horses, heavy enough to destroy field fortifications almost a mile away, and versatile enough to fire solid shot, shell, spherical case, and canister." The French Army introduced the *"canon obusier de 12"* in 1853.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] This type of "canon obusier", commonly called in English the 12-pounder Napoleon Model 1857, was the primary cannon used in the American Civil War.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] Over 1,100 such Napoleons were manufactured by the North, and 600 by the South.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] At Gettysburg, 142 out of 360 Union guns (39%) were Napoleons.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The "12-pounder Napoleon" was widely admired because of its safety, reliability, and killing power, especially at close range.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] It was the last cast bronze gun used by an American army.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The Union version of the Napoleon can be recognized by the flared front end of the barrel, called the muzzle swell.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] Confederate Napoleons were produced in at least six variations, most of which had straight muzzles, but at least eight cataloged survivors of 133 identified have muzzle swells.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] The smoothbore "canon obusier" was soon superseded by rifled cannons, which had much more accuracy and range, with the developments of Antoine Treuille de Beaulieu and the introduction of the La Hitte system in 1858.
[src:carabine-à-tige/canon-obusier-de-12] Napoleon III had his existing guns, such as the Canon obusier de 12, rifled to accommodate the La Hitte system.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The **carabine à tige** (French: [kaʁabin a tiʒ]), sometimes called a **stem rifle** or **pillar breech rifle**, was a type of black-powder, muzzle-loading rifle invented by Louis-Etienne de Thouvenin.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The method was an improvement of the invention of another Frenchman, Henri-Gustave Delvigne.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] When fired, the bullet accompanied the rifling and spun.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] This was an early attempt to work around one of the greatest hindrances to the use of military rifles; in order for a rifle to impart the proper spin to a projectile, the projectile must fit snugly inside the barrel to engage the rifling grooves.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The problem, however, was that the black powder used at that time would quickly produce a thick layer residue of fouling.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] After only three or four shots, a typical rifle would be impossible to reload without using a mallet to force the bullet down the fouled barrel.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] Delvigne's design addressed this problem by introducing a projectile that was smaller than the bore of the barrel (so more easily bypassing the accumulation of fouling) which after loading could then be struck with a ramrod.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] With three strokes of the ramrod, the bullet would become deformed and flatten, so as to expand in diameter against the inside of the bore, allowing the bullet to press against the rifling grooves.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] When fired, the bullet would accompany the rifling and spin.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] This improvement preserved accuracy while reducing the time required for reloading which would otherwise have been necessitated by the heavy fouling.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] Thouvenin's improvement involved a steel stem inside and at the center of the powder chamber, around which powder was inserted, and on top of which the bullet was dropped.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] When hit by the ram, the bullet expanded radially against the rifling grooves and at the same time wrapped around the stem, giving it a more efficient and aerodynamic shape.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] Thouvenin published his invention in 1844.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] This system, although an improvement over Delvigne's method, still did not allow for a perfect engagement in the rifle, rendering the ball's trajectory rather erratic.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The French Army, however, adopted the improvement in 1846.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The Chasseurs adopted the system in 1853, as did the Prussian Jägers corps, where marksmen skills were essential.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The rifles were known as Thouvenin *tige* rifles ("carabines à tige Thouvenin").
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The weapons used a 600 yards sight and a hair trigger.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The barrels were rifled with eight grooves, making a turn every 36 inches.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The Thouvenin rifles had the inconvenience of being very difficult to clean, especially the area around the stem.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] This development was a precursor to the invention of the Minié ball by Claude-Étienne Minié, as Thouvenin had already suggested that a bullet with a hollowed base would be most efficient.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] Minié further developed his iron *culot*, with the objective of forcing the bullet outwards towards the groove through the impact of the *culot* against the inertia of the lead ball, in the same way as the Thouvenin stem, before even making without the *culot*.
[src:carabine-à-tige/carabine-à-tige] The much simpler system superseded the Thouvenin *tige* gun, even allowing the transformation of any smoothbore into a powerful rifled gun ("*fusil rayé*"), simply by the making of rifling grooves and use of the appropriate Minié bullet available to all the troops of the line.
